00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:28.219
So I'm definitely not the right person to advice about, like, physically migrating this.

00:17:28.219 --> 00:17:33.900
My naive approach would be, depending on the project size, I'm dumping records and I'm adding

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:37.819
new records to the new system. That just comes to mind as the way that I would probably approach it.

00:17:40.300 --> 00:17:42.939
Are there any built-in options in PositConnect?

00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:47.579
At the moment, what we've built in is the ability to have secret

00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:52.140
environment variable management to go out to these external services. We have thought about,

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:56.300
like, what kind of integrations we could do to spin up something next to an application you put out

00:17:56.300 --> 00:18:01.180
there. I think one thing that is nice, from a software engineering point of view, I don't know

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:05.579
if this is the right way. One thing that is nice about using that external storage from the start

00:18:05.579 --> 00:18:10.219
is that I can use it locally as well. And there's not this, like, hiccup going between what might

00:18:10.219 --> 00:18:13.260
be supported there. So if we were to build something like that on Connect Cloud, we'd

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:17.260
want it to almost be standalone of the application itself. So it could be set up in advance,

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:21.020
and then you could just attach various ones to it. Something we're open to, though. If anyone

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:24.780
wants to talk about that one with me, please track me down after the session.

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:29.979
Okay. One last question. How do you handle writes to DuckDB in S3?

00:18:30.619 --> 00:18:35.180
How do I handle writes to DuckDB? So from what I understand, and, like, this was me testing it,

00:18:35.180 --> 00:18:40.540
like, on just two or three browsers open. It's so quickly. Like, you go out there and you're

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:44.060
writing something. While something is being written to it, I think it locks down. And if

00:18:44.060 --> 00:18:47.900
another request comes in, it's going to say, right now this is being locked. And unless,

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:52.939
my guess would be, unless you built in that kind of error handling to your application specifically,

00:18:52.939 --> 00:18:58.060
you wouldn't, you probably couldn't handle it. So that was my understanding. And then

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:01.579
MotherDuck sort of takes care of those multiple ones by, like, parsing them out into a queue,

00:19:01.579 --> 00:19:06.540
and then probably passing them in at some stage. All right. Thank you, Alex. Let's thank Alex again.

00:19:14.060 --> 00:19:14.560
Thank you.

